docs: add comprehensive README for OpenTelemetry Docker setup
- Add a README file explaining the project setup and structure - Provide instructions for Docker deployment of OpenTelemetry - Detail the setup for Dockerfile.nginx to build an Nginx image with OpenTelemetry module - Describe the services and configurations in docker-compose.yml for Nginx, OpenTelemetry Collector, Prometheus, and Grafana - Include instructions for configuring Nginx with OpenTelemetry in opentelemetry_module.conf - Outline the configuration for OpenTelemetry Collector in otel-collector-config.yml - Provide Prometheus configuration for scraping metrics from OpenTelemetry Collector in prometheus.yml - Include usage instructions for cloning the repository, starting Docker, and accessing services - Reference additional resources for further information on OpenTelemetry and related tools - Indicate that the project is released under the MIT License

Step 1: Create the directory structure First, we'll create the directory structure you specified: mkdir ~/srt This command creates a new directory named "srt" in your home directory (~). Step 2: Change ownership Next, we'll change the ownership of the newly created directory: sudo chown 1000:0 ~/srt This command changes the owner of the directory to user ID 1000 and group ID 0 (root). Note that you need sudo privileges to perform this operation. Step 3: Set permissions Now, let's set the permissions for the directory: sudo chmod 775 ~/srt This sets read, write, and execute permissions for the owner, read and execute permissions for the group, and read and execute permissions for others. Step 4: Change to the directory Let's navigate to the newly created directory: cd ~/srt This command changes your current working directory to ~/srt. Step 5: Run the Docker command Finally, let's execute the Docker command: docker run --gpus all -it -v ".:/app" -v whisper_cache:/.cache ghcr.io/jim60105/whisperx:latest -- --model large-v3 --language en --output_format srt audio.mp3 Let's break down this Docker command: docker run : This starts a new Docker container. --gpus all : This allocates all available GPUs to the container. -it : This keeps STDIN open and allocates a pseudo-TTY. -v ".:/app" : This mounts the current directory (.) to /app in the container. -v whisper_cache:/.cache : This mounts a volume named whisper_cache to /.cache in the container. ghcr.io/jim60105/whisperx:latest : This specifies the Docker image to use. -- : This separates the Docker run options from the command to be executed in the container. --model large-v3 --language en --output_format srt audio.mp3 : These are the arguments passed to the WhisperX application inside the container. Explanation of what happened: We created a directory named "srt" in your home folder. We changed the ownership of this directory to user ID 1000 and group ID 0. We set the permissions of the directory to 775, allowing full control for the owner and read/write access for others. We navigated into the newly created directory. We started a Docker container based on the WhisperX image. Inside the container, we mounted our current directory and a whisper_cache volume. We instructed the WhisperX application to use the large-v3 model, English language, and output format SRT. We provided an input audio file named "audio.mp3".
This setup allows you to run the WhisperX application on your local machine, utilizing GPU acceleration if available, and process audio files stored in your current directory.
